data.text:
I never bought a new Bigsby before... It has 3 little felt dots on the bottom and I assume that these are peeled off when it is mounted to the guitar permanently so it sits flush against the body. I have no expectations of ever not having a Bigsby on this guitar and I drilled the mount holes for it..

Attachments

20140416_224942.jpg

That looks sweet. Don't be afraid to squirt a liberal amount of graphite powder inside the roller bar on the Bigsby (and take the Bigsby off the body to do this).

I like that color.... it's not too often that you see green used on a Tele. That neck looks real good, I have been waiting to find the right piece of Birdseye. I've enjoyed following your build!

I like that color.... it's not too often that you see green used on a Tele. That neck looks real good, I have been waiting to find the right piece of Birdseye. I've enjoyed following your build!

No doubt. I've always fantasized about a green finish w gold hardware. Maybe Fastback green, or candy apple with a little metallic sparkle to snazzy it up a touch?

Great build Mike.

I think the green is an excellent throw back to the Gretsch color schemes. And it just plain looks cool. You nailed this one Mike. Great job.

Thanks friends.

I got home late from work last night and I didn't get much done... I have a gig tonight 7pm to 11pm at The Desert Eagle Brewery in Mesa and tomorrow afternoon 2pm to 6pm at The Spirit Room in Jerome. Jerome is a 2 1/2 hour drive each way but it is a really cool gig. I won't get back to this until Saturday night or Sunday.

Today I wired up the pots and output jack. I used an old control plate to hold the pots the right distance apart. Drilled the screw holes for the electro socket and the back cover plate.

Attachments

20140420_154537.jpg

20140420_155743.jpg

I made the nut from a bone I buy at Petsmart. Sliced it up on the bandsaw and shaped it on the belt sander.
